Architecture plan for issues #63-#66

Repository shape
- Frontend: React + TypeScript + Vite under src/.
- Desktop backend: Tauri 2 Rust app under src-tauri/.
- LaTeX compilation lives primarily in src-tauri/src/compile.rs.
- Runtime configuration is exposed from src-tauri/src/config.rs to the frontend config types/hooks.
- Ignore policy is managed in the repo-root .gitignore.

Shared module/file organization
- Keep tool discovery in src-tauri/src/compile.rs unless it grows large enough to justify a later toolchain module.
- Use the existing internal Tool struct as the shared representation for detected tools: display name plus executable path.
- Add small pure helpers for discovery:
  - binary_name(name): existing executable-name normalization.
  - candidate executable validation via --version.
  - get_known_toolchain_directories(): returns likely bin directories for the current OS.
  - find_tool_in_known_paths(name): scans those directories after explicit env override and PATH checks.
  - optionally expose a config-facing helper that returns the detected active directory, avoiding duplicated path logic in config.rs.
- Keep compile strategy metadata unchanged, extending only engine choices/log messages as needed.

Issue dependencies and sequencing
1. #66 is independent and can be done any time: add dist/, src-tauri/gen/, src-tauri/target/, .env.local, and *.log to .gitignore and untrack any matching build artifacts if present.
2. #63 should land before #64 because fallback engine selection should reuse the broader tool discovery path.
3. #64 depends on #63 discovery and updates compile_document() control flow to retry manual passes when MiKTeX latexmk fails due to missing Perl; also adds lualatex as an engine candidate.
4. #65 depends on the compile tests added/updated for #63/#64, and should make fake tool executables work on Windows by writing .cmd stubs while preserving Unix shell stubs.

Key design decisions
- Precedence: explicit LATEX_TOOLCHAIN_PATH / VITE_LATEX_TOOLCHAIN_PATH always wins, then process PATH, then known install directories.
- Known Windows directories should include per-user MiKTeX under LOCALAPPDATA, system MiKTeX under Program Files, and TeX Live under C:\\texlive\\<year> bin paths; scan newest TeX Live years first when possible.
- macOS/Linux discovery should cover common TeX Live/MacTeX and Tectonic locations without assuming shell startup files have populated PATH.
- Detection should validate executables with --version, but compile-time fallback must distinguish latexmk's missing-Perl runtime failure from normal LaTeX failures to avoid hiding real document errors.
- Manual engine preference should be deterministic, likely pdflatex, xelatex, then lualatex unless the existing UI/config later introduces an engine choice.
- Logs should make fallback behavior visible so users can understand why latexmk was skipped and which native engine compiled the document.
- Tests should avoid depending on real LaTeX installations except the existing ignored E2E-style test; unit tests should use temp fake toolchains and cross-platform script generation.

Validation plan
- Run npm test to cover TypeScript and Rust unit tests wired through the project test script.
- Run cargo test --manifest-path src-tauri/Cargo.toml directly for backend changes.
- Run npm run build for production TypeScript/Vite validation.
- For real-machine acceptance, verify MiKTeX/TeX Live detection when the install bin directory is absent from PATH, and verify MiKTeX latexmk without Perl falls back to a native engine.
